- String objects are immutable, so every modification creates a new object.
- StringBuilder is mutable, so it changes the existing object.
- This makes StringBuilder much faster for operations like concatenation, reversing, inserting, and deleting.

Common Methods : 
class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String s = "Hello";
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Hello");
        sb.append("Program");
        System.out.println(sb.reverse());
        sb.insert(5,"!");
        System.out.println(sb);
        System.out.println(sb.length());
        sb.delete(2,5);
        System.out.println(sb);
        sb.replace(0,2, "*");
        System.out.println(sb);
        System.out.println(sb.charAt(2));
        sb.setCharAt(0, 'k');
        System.out.println(sb);
        
        
        
    }
}
